urn off (4.6\n$\\sigma$) at the highest energies, which can be described with an exponential\ncut-off at $E_c = 3.5\\left(^{+1.6}_{-1.0}\\right)_{\\textit{stat}}\n\\left(^{+0.8}_{-0.9}\\right)_{\\textit{sys}}$ TeV. The gamma-ray emission from 60\nMeV to 10 TeV can be attributed to a population of high-energy protons with\nspectral index $\\sim$2.2 and energy cut-off at $\\sim$10 TeV. This result\nindicates that Cas A is not contributing to the high energy ($\\sim$PeV)\ncosmic-ray sea in a significant manner at the present moment. A one-zone\nleptonic model fails to reproduce by itself the multi-wavelength spectral\nenergy distribution. Besides, if a non-negligible fraction of the flux seen by\nMAGIC is produced by leptons, the radiation should be emitted in a region with\na low magnetic field (B$\\lessapprox$100$\\mu$G) like in the reverse shock.)\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 5 Jul 2017 21:22:12 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-01-30"}
